Spatiotemporal properties of evoked neural response in the primary visual cortex

a PhD thesis by Jean-Luc Richard Stevens

Reproducibility

This notebook reproduces the figures generated for the third chapter of my thesis, A reproducible workflow for exploratory research, which can be downloaded here.

This chapter describes two open source projects that were crucial for delivering the final thesis, namely Lancet and HoloViews. Lancet is a general tool for specifying, launching and managing large numbers of batch jobs and was used to launch all the simulations presented in Stevens et al. (2013). HoloViews is a library of declarative, visualizable and composable objects used in all the notebooks that are part of this thesis. All output from the Topographica neural simulator displayed in the notebook environment is in the form of HoloViews objects.

Figure 3.1 : Examples of Arguments objects that were used to define the parameter space explored in Chapter 5.
Figure 3.2 : Example of how HoloViews can be used to explore a simulation of the model analyzed in Chapter 5.

Figure 3.1 (Lancet Argument objects)¶

Figure 3.1 : Examples of Arguments objects that were used to define the parameter space explored in Chapter 5.

The following three executable reprs were used to construct this figure. The first shows how you can define a very simple parameter space of 21 contrast values between zero and 100% contrast that were used in the GCAL simulations presented in Stevens et al. (2013):

@article{Stevens2013,
    author = {Stevens, Jean-Luc R. and Law, Judith S. and
    Antol\'{i}k, J\'{a}n and Bednar, James A.},
    title = {Mechanisms for Stable, Robust, and Adaptive Development 
             of Orientation Maps in the Primary Visual Cortex},
journal = {The Journal of Neuroscience},
    volume = {33},
    number = {40},
    pages = {15747-15766},
    year = {2013},
    doi = {10.1523/JNEUROSCI.1037-13.2013},
    url = {http://www.jneurosci.org/content/33/40/15747.full}
}

Figure 3.2 (HoloViews and GCAL)¶

Figure 3.2 : Example of how HoloViews can be used to explore a simulation of the model analyzed in Chapter 4.

This figure demonstrates how HoloViews was used to visualize and explore the properties of GCAL model presented in Chapter 4. In particular, the orientation preference and selectivity of the GCAL model is shown across development, together with concurrent pinwheel analysis.

In [5]:
import holoviews as hv
hv.notebook_extension()
HoloViewsJS successfully loaded in this cell.

First topographica, the GCAL model and corresponding analysis and measurement functions need to be imported:

In [6]:
import topo
from topo.submodel.gcal import ModelGCAL

import featuremapper
from featuremapper.command import measure_or_pref, measure_response, measure_sine_pref
from featuremapper.analysis.hypercolumns import PowerSpectrumAnalysis
from featuremapper.analysis.pinwheels import PinwheelAnalysis

from topo.analysis import Collector

Next the GCAL model is initialized:

In [7]:
topo.sim.model = ModelGCAL(cortex_density=98)
topo.sim() # Initialize the model

The relevant measurements are declared:

In [8]:
c = Collector()
# Preference map measurement (e.g. for orientation and center of gravity plots)
c.collect(measure_or_pref)

And then executed periodically over the course of development:

In [9]:
times = [100*i for i in range(31)]
data = c(times=times)

Completion:
100% measurement progress 00:00:16

Next some HoloViews plot and style options are set to demonstrate how visualizations can be customized using HoloViews:

In [10]:
%opts Image [sublabel_format='{roman}'] 
%opts Overlay [show_legend=False sublabel_format='{roman}']
%opts Points.Pinwheels (color='k' s=30)

And now we can interactively explore the development of orientation preference and selectivity while also viewing the output of the pinwheel analysis:

In [11]:
%opts Points.Pinwheels (marker='s')
layout = data.OrientationSelectivity.V1 + PinwheelAnalysis(data.OrientationPreference.V1)
layout
Out[11]:

Using HoloViews select method, we can view the results after 500 iterations, as shown in the top row of Figure 3.2A:

In [12]:
layout.select(Time=500)
Out[12]:

And then the results after 2500 iterations, as shown in the bottom row of Figure 3.2A:

In [13]:
layout.select(Time=2500)
Out[13]:
